WEBVTT

01:10.470 --> 01:12.930
Eye movement detected.

01:27.790 --> 01:31.550
What is 2 plus 2?

01:33.090 --> 01:34.090
Incorrect.

01:35.650 --> 01:36.530
Cognition assessment.

01:37.810 --> 01:39.330
What is 2 plus 2?

01:40.430 --> 01:40.930
Incorrect.

01:40.930 --> 01:44.650
You have been in a
medically induced coma.

01:46.870 --> 01:48.850
You may experience memory loss,

01:49.530 --> 01:50.570
difficulty speaking.

01:54.350 --> 01:55.730
Body movement detected.

01:57.050 --> 01:59.970
For your own safety, please
return to the medical platform.

02:05.334 --> 02:06.054
<i>Good Luck!</i>

02:07.334 --> 02:10.054
<i>Location: Medical Arm</i>

02:08.930 --> 02:13.390
Please remember, muscle function
has not yet been restored.

02:19.690 --> 02:20.390
No.

02:28.170 --> 02:29.570
People!

02:30.830 --> 02:31.450
Hello!

02:45.210 --> 02:46.610
Oh.

02:46.292 --> 02:49.621
<i>YAO. L.J. : Deceased</i>

03:16.790 --> 03:18.450
Where am I?

04:06.190 --> 04:10.050
Why is there an atomic resolution
scanning electron microscope?

04:10.670 --> 04:12.490
Why do I know that?

04:13.490 --> 04:14.490
Am I smart?

04:51.210 --> 04:51.410
Hello?

04:52.950 --> 04:55.210
Please record video diary. No.

04:57.210 --> 04:58.090
in charge?

04:59.090 --> 05:01.070
The captain.

05:01.330 --> 05:03.550
Captain Yao Li-Jie. Deceased.

05:03.730 --> 05:07.110
Yeah. Where are
the living people?

05:08.130 --> 05:09.830
Dr. Ryland Grace.

05:11.050 --> 05:12.230
End of manifest.

05:14.870 --> 05:19.250
I can't be the only
person here, right?

05:20.150 --> 05:21.130
Pilot detected.

05:21.350 --> 05:23.690
No, no, no, not the pilot.

05:24.830 --> 05:26.750
Uh, call, uh, Houston.

05:26.750 --> 05:28.890
Unknown command.

05:29.390 --> 05:31.810
Operation go home in effect.

05:32.330 --> 05:33.210
Invalid operation.

05:34.610 --> 05:35.770
That's the sun!

05:36.850 --> 05:37.610
There it is.

05:37.930 --> 05:40.110
So, what are we
like Neptune-ish?

05:41.850 --> 05:44.710
Let's crank up the
radio and call Earth.

05:44.970 --> 05:46.570
Current transmission
time to Earth

05:46.610 --> 05:51.390
is 11 years, 10 months,
14 days and 6 hours.

05:52.190 --> 05:54.790
No. Nope. You're wrong.

05:54.790 --> 05:57.210
I need a map.

05:58.390 --> 05:59.050
Oh.

06:00.610 --> 06:03.650
That's really far.

06:15.550 --> 06:17.190
That's not our sun.

06:20.170 --> 06:23.450
That's not our sun.

06:36.230 --> 06:39.090
Where is the fuel?

06:41.480 --> 06:42.933
<i>Fuel Level: Low</i>

06:44.070 --> 06:45.470
Wait.

06:48.251 --> 06:50.556
<i>Rate= 6 g/s = 6 x 310
Fuel= 11.581 kg</i>

07:20.170 --> 07:25.210
We are just minutes away from the
flyby through the Petrova line near Venus.

07:25.670 --> 07:27.890
So, what can you tell us
about the ArcLight probe?

07:28.092 --> 07:30.032
<i>ArcLight seeks to unlock mystery of the Petrova Line</i>

07:28.570 --> 07:31.010
What do we expect to find?

07:32.390 --> 07:35.550
The image we see will be coming
from the onboard microscope.

07:39.950 --> 07:41.510
Oh! Oh my God!

07:46.170 --> 07:47.710
Sorry, I have to go now.

07:50.170 --> 07:54.170
Oh my God!

07:57.850 --> 08:01.650
Sound waves are physical

08:02.790 --> 08:05.550
and at different frequencies

08:07.250 --> 08:10.490
they make different patterns.

08:11.350 --> 08:11.670
Patterns.

08:11.790 --> 08:13.110
They make different patterns.

08:13.210 --> 08:14.190
Olivia, can you help me out?

08:14.530 --> 08:14.850
Try going.

08:14.910 --> 08:15.610
There we go.

08:16.610 --> 08:17.290
Whoa!

08:19.070 --> 08:19.670
Yeah?

08:20.370 --> 08:21.590
Are they really eating the sun?

08:22.310 --> 08:23.910
The space dots?

08:24.150 --> 08:25.710
That is a great
question, uh, Rekha.

08:26.350 --> 08:29.390
I'd be curious what your
parents think about that?

08:29.490 --> 08:31.510
I'm not sure it
should come from me.

08:31.590 --> 08:34.730
Hey, who wants to
play a game of...

08:34.730 --> 08:35.690
The beanbag is lava!

08:36.290 --> 08:38.570
Lava! Lava! Lava!

08:38.570 --> 08:41.170
What is the speed
of light, Olivia?

08:42.350 --> 08:44.090
Uh... It's melting
your hands, Olivia!

08:44.090 --> 08:46.890
186,000 miles per second!

08:47.130 --> 08:48.870
Oh! Give her a
round of applause.

08:49.050 --> 08:50.210
That is awesome!

08:50.990 --> 08:53.290
What is the Petrova line?

08:53.870 --> 08:55.150
Ha ha ha! Pass!

08:55.650 --> 08:56.670
You can't pass.

08:58.250 --> 09:02.010
Lava! Lava! Lava!

09:02.070 --> 09:03.170
Two years ago,

09:04.710 --> 09:08.350
a radio telescope enthusiast
named Irina Petrova,

09:09.530 --> 09:12.190
she noticed that there was
a streak of infrared light

09:12.190 --> 09:14.170
from the sun to Venus.

09:14.870 --> 09:17.370
And that is now known
as the Petrova line.

09:17.610 --> 09:18.390
That's it.

09:18.470 --> 09:19.650
That's the dots?

09:20.170 --> 09:21.030
They think so.

09:21.650 --> 09:22.110
What dots?

09:25.970 --> 09:26.890
These dots.

09:28.230 --> 09:30.050
They sent a probe up
to the Petrova line,

09:30.070 --> 09:31.810
and this is what they found.

09:33.510 --> 09:35.250
Are they eating the sun?

09:36.990 --> 09:40.110
They seem to be dimming the sun

09:40.270 --> 09:43.110
a tiny, teeny, weeny little bit.

09:44.090 --> 09:45.170
So no big whoop.

09:45.450 --> 09:46.710
It's a small whoop.

09:47.330 --> 09:48.690
It's a small to medium whoop.

09:48.690 --> 09:52.650
Over the next 30
years, the Earth could

09:53.310 --> 09:55.690
cool maybe 10 to

09:57.110 --> 09:58.110
15 degrees.

09:59.610 --> 10:00.530
So it is a big whoop.

10:00.930 --> 10:03.090
I heard that all
the crops will die,

10:03.090 --> 10:04.530
die, the economy will free fall,

10:04.530 --> 10:06.570
and half the Earth
will die of starvation.

10:08.270 --> 10:09.850
We're all gonna die.

10:10.650 --> 10:11.250
Yeah, it's true.

10:11.570 --> 10:12.710
You're forgetting something.

10:12.990 --> 10:16.030
Guys, guys, that's if
that were to happen, right?

10:16.410 --> 10:17.890
They're gonna figure this out.

10:17.890 --> 10:21.870
Right now, the best
minds in the entire world

10:22.890 --> 10:23.890
are on it.

10:38.315 --> 10:45.127
Well, I woke up Sunday morning with no
way to hold my head and it didn't hurt.

10:39.005 --> 10:41.081
<i>VODKA</i>

10:48.890 --> 10:50.390
Good morning, Dr. Grace.

10:52.170 --> 10:53.670
I'm up.

11:01.442 --> 11:03.325
<i>Commander Yao</i>

11:12.619 --> 11:14.118
<i>ILYUKHINA</i>

11:30.847 --> 11:37.213
Wishing, Lord,
that I was stoned.

11:31.330 --> 11:33.159
<i>Who am I?</i>

11:33.322 --> 11:34.760
<i>Grace</i>

11:37.233 --> 11:48.985
Cause there's something in a
Sunday that makes a body feel alone.

11:37.987 --> 11:41.244
<i>Ah!: The Element of Surprise</i>

11:41.892 --> 11:43.446
<i>Always Muscles?? "have I always been muscular?"
Friends?</i>

11:49.005 --> 11:54.730
And there's nothing
short of dying.

11:54.751 --> 11:57.293
Half as lonesome as it sounds.

12:00.530 --> 12:09.663
On the sleeping city side
walls Sunday morning coming down

12:06.149 --> 12:08.204
<i>How did I get here?</i>

12:25.778 --> 12:27.625
<i>Sun</i>

12:32.590 --> 12:33.610
Knock, knock.

12:36.030 --> 12:36.630
Who's there?

12:37.390 --> 12:37.930
Not good at jokes.

12:38.430 --> 12:39.210
Not good at jokes, who?

12:43.350 --> 12:44.390
Dr. Grace.

12:46.950 --> 12:51.070
Maybe. Eva Stratt, I'm with the
Petrova task force. I need your help.

12:52.230 --> 12:53.790
Me. Did you write this?

12:53.968 --> 12:54.995
<i>An Analysis Of Water Based Assumptions</i>

12:55.019 --> 12:56.850
<i>and Recalibrations of Expectations
for Evolutionary Models</i>

12:57.210 --> 13:00.970
Oh. I'm interested in
this section here, page 31.

13:01.650 --> 13:05.530
The Goldilocks Zone is for idiots,
why everyone is wrong about life.

13:06.170 --> 13:07.490
That was a long time ago.

13:07.970 --> 13:08.890
Did you stand by what you wrote?

13:09.070 --> 13:11.570
I was fired for
standing by what I wrote.

13:11.910 --> 13:15.290
You were fired for calling the
leading scholar in your field a

13:15.290 --> 13:19.010
a staggering waste of carbon at
the UNESCO conference in Denmark?

13:19.010 --> 13:20.610
You-- You heard about that, huh?

13:21.450 --> 13:26.210
Look, I don't know what
this is, but, uh, I think, uh

13:26.210 --> 13:27.350
I'm not su-- That's lava.

13:27.950 --> 13:28.990
It's not. Okay.

13:30.090 --> 13:32.030
No one in your field wants
anything to do with you

13:32.030 --> 13:34.730
because you refuse to back
down from a very unpopular view,

13:34.730 --> 13:36.630
and I can give you a chance
to prove them all wrong.

13:36.630 --> 13:38.610
Uh, that's uh--
Kevin, no running.

13:38.730 --> 13:39.210
I'm not.

13:40.190 --> 13:42.420
Joke's on them because
I don't even care, so...

13:44.070 --> 13:45.850
I think you do care.

13:45.930 --> 13:47.570
You're just running away
because you're scared.

13:48.070 --> 13:48.350
No, I'm not.

13:50.910 --> 13:54.170
Do you still believe water is
unnecessary for life to evolve?

13:55.690 --> 13:59.470
Look, there is nothing magical
about hydrogen and oxygen.

13:59.990 --> 14:02.070
Water is required for
life on Earth, sure,

14:02.170 --> 14:04.990
but a completely different planet might
have completely different conditions.

14:05.090 --> 14:06.930
I don't know why that
makes me such a nut.

14:07.070 --> 14:08.310
I need you to come with us.

14:10.070 --> 14:11.920
Sorry, I didn't
catch your name Carl.

14:12.570 --> 14:13.390
Carl, hi.

14:13.550 --> 14:14.150
Dr. Grace,

14:14.450 --> 14:16.090
Petrova line samples
splashed down last night.

14:16.130 --> 14:18.350
I want you to tell me what
they are, how they work.

14:19.050 --> 14:21.550
I am a teacher at
Grover Cleveland Middle.

14:21.930 --> 14:23.650
You have a doctorate
in molecular biology.

14:23.810 --> 14:25.430
And I ride a bike to work,

14:25.870 --> 14:27.950
and it's not for exercise,

14:28.030 --> 14:30.430
so I'm sure there are
thousands of other people...

14:30.430 --> 14:31.570
It survives on the
surface of the sun.

14:32.150 --> 14:33.950
Does that sound like a
water-based life form to you?

14:41.430 --> 14:43.150
The sun's really
dying, isn't it?

14:43.274 --> 14:43.394
Yeah.

14:44.930 --> 14:45.410
Yeah.

14:48.070 --> 14:51.190
Is all of this necessary?

14:52.950 --> 14:53.430
Yes.

14:54.470 --> 14:56.150
Please analyze
the Petrova sample.

14:58.490 --> 14:59.410
Just one thing.

14:59.490 --> 15:01.010
The entire room is
filled with argon.

15:01.170 --> 15:02.430
Just try not to rip your suit.

15:06.870 --> 15:08.330
Am I expendable?

15:08.570 --> 15:09.570
Is that what you want me?

15:09.570 --> 15:11.350
That's not the only reason.

15:12.070 --> 15:13.850
It's almost like you
don't care if I die.

15:18.170 --> 15:19.950
Hold on. You have
to talk about it?

15:21.010 --> 15:25.570
Consensus here is that it would
be preferable if you did not die.

15:27.350 --> 15:28.530
Thanks guys.

15:35.947 --> 15:36.148
Oh.

15:42.170 --> 15:43.150
to Earth.

15:58.690 --> 15:59.830
Are they alive?

16:01.050 --> 16:02.010
They're moving.

16:02.630 --> 16:03.530
So they're alive.

16:04.410 --> 16:07.590
Yes, they're moving, but
that could be for many reasons.

16:07.890 --> 16:08.850
What are they made of?

16:09.130 --> 16:13.610
It's going to take a long time. It took like
200 years to figure out how bacteria work.

16:13.610 --> 16:14.550
Please do it faster.

16:17.290 --> 16:19.550
I'm just going through the
whole light spectrum here.

16:21.010 --> 16:22.010
Wow!

16:24.230 --> 16:25.390
You're not going
to believe this.

16:28.810 --> 16:29.630
Nothing happened.

16:34.070 --> 16:37.390
I can't see into these

16:39.370 --> 16:40.030
Amazing.

16:41.350 --> 16:45.150
microwaves, gamma rays,
visible light. Nothing!

16:48.050 --> 16:55.630
I've been dying
to do this all day.

17:06.890 --> 17:08.150
It's a cell.

17:08.420 --> 17:10.590
It's a cell... Wake
up! It's a cell!

17:11.390 --> 17:13.410
It's a tiny alien cell.

17:13.670 --> 17:14.410
You guys!

17:14.410 --> 17:15.130
Applause.

17:15.130 --> 17:23.150
Guys! This is first contact!
It's life! Outside of the...

17:23.150 --> 17:23.590
Uh-oh.

17:24.690 --> 17:26.150
Oh, it died.

17:27.190 --> 17:27.550
What?

17:28.350 --> 17:30.090
This is great news.

17:30.350 --> 17:32.490
Now we can find out
what they're made of.

17:34.690 --> 17:36.410
You guys fired up?

17:39.910 --> 17:40.130
Yes!

17:40.258 --> 17:40.739
Yes!

17:41.870 --> 17:42.610
Right?

17:43.610 --> 17:45.070
Carbon.

17:46.406 --> 17:47.168
Oxygen.

17:50.270 --> 17:50.950
Hydrogen.

17:52.410 --> 17:52.690
Oh.

18:07.816 --> 18:08.577
It's made.

18:09.790 --> 18:12.590
It's made...

18:14.490 --> 18:16.250
of water.

18:26.170 --> 18:27.170
Alright.

18:30.330 --> 18:38.070
Sorry if I overreacted in there. Just, uh, realizing
I was wrong about the only original idea I ever had.

18:38.310 --> 18:39.450
Yeah, what else did you learn?

18:40.210 --> 18:45.110
They give off infrared light when they move.
Like so much, I don't know how they store

18:45.110 --> 18:51.050
store all that energy. But their wavelength
is exactly the Petrova frequency.

18:51.290 --> 18:52.630
Their light is how they move.

18:52.830 --> 18:58.470
Yeah, they consume the sun's energy and then they
expel it for propulsion. They toot to scoot, basically.

19:00.670 --> 19:01.990
Why did it go to Venus?

19:04.270 --> 19:05.310
I don't know.

19:07.290 --> 19:09.690
Okay, we'll tell you. What?

19:09.690 --> 19:15.920
I have 347 other biologists in 21 countries
mobilizing as we speak, so thank you for your help.

19:16.070 --> 19:17.210
I'm glad you didn't die.

19:17.210 --> 19:18.630
Let's pack this up!

19:23.010 --> 19:23.810
That's it?!

19:25.110 --> 19:25.570
That's it, Carl?

19:25.850 --> 19:26.430
Talk to her.

19:26.910 --> 19:28.090
You're taking all this stuff?

19:28.390 --> 19:31.890
At the school you said there were thousands
of people more qualified than you, so...

19:31.890 --> 19:32.770
I was being modest.

19:32.990 --> 19:36.970
I don't need modest. I need people who think they're
right when everyone else thinks they're wrong.

19:36.970 --> 19:38.710
I need people who
piss other people off.

19:38.710 --> 19:39.550
That's me!

19:39.830 --> 19:40.650
Do you want to
be on our project?

19:42.070 --> 19:47.730
If you... If you think I can help,
then... Just answer the question.

19:48.970 --> 19:50.910
I want to help the world.

19:51.010 --> 19:52.030
I left you three dots.

19:52.950 --> 19:53.990
Just three, huh?

19:54.210 --> 19:54.970
Plus the one you killed.

19:56.430 --> 19:57.350
I would take the three.

20:00.230 --> 20:01.690
Yes? I'll take the dots.

20:02.090 --> 20:03.210
Get to work, Dr. Grace.

20:04.690 --> 20:07.450
The world is counting on you.

21:11.640 --> 21:13.484
<i>Astrophage
Why Venus ???</i>

21:15.290 --> 21:15.730
Hey, Carl?

21:17.750 --> 21:18.450
This is Carl.

21:19.130 --> 21:23.110
Imagine... for a second that
you're an interstellar microorganism.

21:23.710 --> 21:24.490
I'm not doing that.

21:26.790 --> 21:28.530
Why would you leave
the Sun and go to Venus?

21:29.710 --> 21:32.330
Why not stop at
Mercury, it's closer?

21:33.950 --> 21:34.990
Maybe fresh air?

21:35.750 --> 21:37.330
Venus's atmosphere
is mostly CO2.

21:37.570 --> 21:39.010
Maybe that's fresh air to them.

21:39.350 --> 21:40.910
You don't know what doing
a little space dust like?

21:44.587 --> 21:45.759
<i>Berlin . Stockholm . Beijing
Cape Town . Mexico City . Tokyo</i>

21:45.802 --> 21:46.746
<i>Cambridge . Milan . Sao Paulo</i>

21:46.530 --> 21:47.270
Hey Carl,

21:48.270 --> 21:49.690
do we have an expense account?

21:49.920 --> 21:51.190
We don't.

21:56.270 --> 21:57.110
But, I do.

22:16.788 --> 22:20.733
Thank you.

22:39.770 --> 22:41.170
Thank you.

22:41.510 --> 22:42.390
Do you have a coupon?

22:42.770 --> 22:44.410
We don't need a coupon.
We're the government.

22:44.810 --> 22:45.410
Which government?

22:46.090 --> 22:46.650
All of them.

22:49.230 --> 22:50.870
So this box is Venus?

22:51.010 --> 22:51.990
The box is Venus.

22:52.570 --> 22:56.190
It's set to emit the same infrared
light frequency as Venus's CO2 atmosphere.

22:56.570 --> 22:58.770
So if the dots move when
you turn the lights on,

22:59.070 --> 23:01.050
that means they're
looking for CO2.

23:01.190 --> 23:02.950
Thus proving the
Carl hypothesis.

23:03.930 --> 23:04.230
Sick.

23:08.490 --> 23:10.530
All right, you ready?

23:15.350 --> 23:15.710
Uh-oh.

23:17.030 --> 23:17.710
Why are you saying, uh-oh?

23:18.370 --> 23:20.130
The astrophage
moved off the slide.

23:21.050 --> 23:21.250
Huh?

23:21.790 --> 23:22.630
We lost them.

23:23.410 --> 23:25.070
What do you mean we
lost them? Go get them.

23:26.110 --> 23:28.670
If I open the door and the
light, they're gonna escape

23:28.730 --> 23:30.690
and then we'll lose them forever.
At least now they're in the box.

23:31.050 --> 23:32.310
So then just turn
the lights off.

23:32.410 --> 23:34.470
They'll still be light.
It's got to be total darkness.

23:34.470 --> 23:42.470
Okay, so just put
this box in another box.

23:58.650 --> 24:00.090
Go ahead and close it over.

24:01.090 --> 24:06.310
I can hear you.

24:07.930 --> 24:10.250
Entering phase two.

24:16.090 --> 24:16.910
I'm in.

24:20.170 --> 24:25.190
Please report over.

24:28.070 --> 24:28.450
There's one.

24:30.590 --> 24:31.550
There's two!

24:32.270 --> 24:34.770
Come on, get the third one.

24:36.310 --> 24:39.370
Got sample three. The three
musketeers - the three stooges.

24:44.710 --> 24:45.390
What?

24:45.790 --> 24:46.470
What?

24:47.630 --> 24:48.830
Are you sitting down?

24:49.410 --> 24:50.150
No, I'm standing up.

24:50.150 --> 24:51.190
I'm standing like a grown man.

24:51.930 --> 24:52.710
'Cause there's a fourth.

24:54.490 --> 24:54.810
What?

24:57.450 --> 24:58.810
We're fathers, Carl.

25:02.030 --> 25:03.290
Now I'm sitting down.

25:07.190 --> 25:07.870
Stop.

25:09.010 --> 25:09.810
Carl and I made a baby.

25:11.350 --> 25:12.030
What?

25:12.750 --> 25:14.630
We figured out how
astrophage breeds.

25:15.110 --> 25:16.170
Don't move.

25:19.230 --> 25:20.030
What's up?

25:23.210 --> 25:27.090
Carl. Strat said she was sending
jets. I thought you meant like a PJ.

25:27.190 --> 25:27.850
I thought you did.

25:27.990 --> 25:28.250
I know.

25:29.190 --> 25:29.990
Take this.

25:31.390 --> 25:34.730
It's been a long time since I've taken a pill
from a stranger without knowing what it was.

25:49.350 --> 25:51.290
Dr. Grace, how was your flight?

25:56.750 --> 25:57.730
Where are we?

25:57.830 --> 25:58.430
The ocean.

25:58.930 --> 26:01.150
The astrophage reproduction,
can you do it at scale?

26:01.150 --> 26:02.450
Oh, in theory.

26:03.350 --> 26:06.870
You just get a bunch of elbow
shaped pipe, put sunlight in one end.

26:07.210 --> 26:08.410
Excuse me for a second.

26:09.070 --> 26:09.890
Write it down.

26:11.750 --> 26:13.990
And IR line CO2 in the other.

26:15.270 --> 26:17.150
Repeat. Anything else
you need for this?

26:17.150 --> 26:17.370
Just some water.

26:17.490 --> 26:19.310
he gave me a pill and
it's still in my throat.

26:19.610 --> 26:20.670
Two venti coffees?

26:20.950 --> 26:21.870
Thank you so much.

26:21.990 --> 26:22.530
Water for him.

26:22.530 --> 26:22.890
Or coffee.

26:23.810 --> 26:24.810
I need both.

26:25.090 --> 26:25.630
Or not.

26:26.130 --> 26:29.750
Okay, so this is kind of a tough room.
So don't take it personally. I don't

26:29.750 --> 26:30.690
I don't need anything fancy.

26:30.910 --> 26:32.990
As long as there's a bed
and a shower, I'm good.

26:38.350 --> 26:39.390
I can't.

26:40.790 --> 26:41.750
You're doing great.

26:42.830 --> 26:45.970
Everyone, this is Dr. Rylan
Grace from the United States.

26:46.170 --> 26:47.150
Please go here.

26:47.210 --> 26:47.730
Thank you.

26:48.070 --> 26:50.910
And he figured out
how to breed astrophage.

26:56.770 --> 26:58.010
How did you do it?

26:58.010 --> 26:59.870
How long does the process take?

27:00.190 --> 27:02.410
Was it reproduced by
mitosis or meiosis?

27:02.530 --> 27:03.750
What is the incubation period?

27:08.830 --> 27:11.690
Carl and I made a mini
venus out of a plywood box.

27:11.882 --> 27:12.855
<i>Germany . India</i>

27:12.290 --> 27:16.910
And as soon as the samples recognized
the spectral signature of CO2,

27:18.010 --> 27:19.090
they were...

27:20.170 --> 27:21.810
Like whoomp, there it is.

27:22.050 --> 27:23.130
Okay, Whoomp, there it is.

27:23.130 --> 27:23.870
you can sit down.

27:24.131 --> 27:24.912
You can sit down in this chair.

27:24.930 --> 27:27.430
While your experiment
was crude and clumsy,

27:27.670 --> 27:30.110
our scientists have
replicated his results.

27:32.450 --> 27:34.890
Sorry, how did you
see, how did you?

27:34.950 --> 27:36.790
We estimate an
eight-day doubling time

27:36.790 --> 27:37.970
under optimal conditions.

27:38.490 --> 27:39.550
Dr. Grace is right.

27:40.010 --> 27:41.990
Oh. It is the CO2.

27:42.110 --> 27:43.270
That's why they're
going to Venus.

27:43.430 --> 27:44.750
you say it for everyone?

27:44.770 --> 27:45.890
That's why they're
going to Venus.

27:46.270 --> 27:49.470
So that's why they're
going to Venus,

27:49.470 --> 27:51.330
Venus, is what
Dr. Grace wants to say?

27:51.470 --> 27:52.370
They're going to breathe.

27:53.350 --> 27:54.810
Whoomp, there it is.

27:56.210 --> 27:58.010
I really like him.

27:58.610 --> 28:00.530
How long to make two
million kilograms?

28:00.970 --> 28:01.670
Two million?

28:04.130 --> 28:08.850
Two million is... Why on Earth

28:08.850 --> 28:10.730
would you need that
much astrophage?

28:11.090 --> 28:12.110
Nobody told him?

28:13.250 --> 28:15.130
He has no clearance.

28:15.130 --> 28:15.870
Stand up, Dr. Grace.

28:16.470 --> 28:17.030
Clearance?

28:17.230 --> 28:17.970
Stand up.

28:19.470 --> 28:21.330
I hereby grant you
top secret clearance

28:21.330 --> 28:23.710
to all information pertaining
to Project Hail Mary.

28:25.210 --> 28:26.330
What's Project Hail Mary?

28:28.670 --> 28:29.390
All right.

28:29.401 --> 28:30.939
<i>What is "Project Hail Mary"?</i>

28:32.990 --> 28:34.870
The sun is not the
only star dying.

28:35.450 --> 28:37.650
There is a clear
pattern of infection.

28:37.950 --> 28:41.030
Every star was infected
by its neighbor except one.

28:42.650 --> 28:45.010
Tau Ceti, that's right,
11.9 light years away.

28:45.090 --> 28:46.870
It is uninfected
despite being well

28:46.870 --> 28:48.250
within the cluster
of infected stars.

28:48.810 --> 28:49.150
Why?

28:49.830 --> 28:50.730
Why? Tell him.

28:50.890 --> 28:52.450
We don't know.

28:52.650 --> 28:54.910
Which is why we
decided to build a ship

28:54.910 --> 28:56.590
ship to go there and find out.

28:57.110 --> 28:58.450
It's 11.9 light years away.

28:58.490 --> 29:00.210
You can't just build
an interstellar ship.

29:00.670 --> 29:01.390
Oh, yeah, we can.

29:01.850 --> 29:03.390
The ship is not
really the problem.

29:03.930 --> 29:06.770
The energy required to
power the ship is the problem.

29:06.990 --> 29:08.250
It was the problem.

29:08.150 --> 29:09.271
<i>Project Hail Mary - FUEL SYSTEM</i>

29:08.570 --> 29:09.310
Weep, weep.

29:09.416 --> 29:10.576
<i>2 Million kg Astrophage Fuel</i>

29:10.510 --> 29:11.970
The astrophage is the fuel.

29:12.250 --> 29:14.290
Provided we can
make enough of it.

29:14.290 --> 29:16.670
And for that, we
need you, my friend.

29:19.190 --> 29:19.750
Me?

29:20.670 --> 29:23.630
Ooh. Those little guys
store a lot of energy.

29:24.210 --> 29:26.590
One mistake in that much
astrophage could vaporize

29:27.370 --> 29:27.930
California.

29:28.370 --> 29:30.510
That's true, which is
why you now live on a boat

29:30.510 --> 29:32.090
boat in the middle of
the ocean in Gainesville.

29:33.090 --> 29:34.230
I live on the boat?

29:34.410 --> 29:34.870
You do.

29:35.770 --> 29:37.770
So you wanna build a
near light speed spaceship,

29:38.330 --> 29:40.750
have it travel further
than any human-made object

29:40.750 --> 29:43.650
has ever traveled,
and visit a star just to

29:44.770 --> 29:46.630
see what's up? Yeah.

29:47.210 --> 29:47.910
And then what?

29:47.910 --> 29:50.250
There won't be enough
fuel for a round trip,

29:50.710 --> 29:53.470
so they send their findings
back to Earth on probes.

29:53.287 --> 29:54.296
<i>Probe in Flight</i>

29:54.390 --> 29:55.429
<i>"Beetle" Prototype Design</i>

29:56.450 --> 29:58.290
And the astronauts

30:01.570 --> 30:02.790
die in space?

30:03.330 --> 30:03.910
Yes.

30:07.070 --> 30:07.750
Space.

30:11.450 --> 30:14.650
Any other plans you thought of?

30:14.650 --> 30:17.210
Anything else? Anything
else you're kicking around?

30:17.210 --> 30:19.590
There are infinite
possibilities.

30:20.170 --> 30:22.750
For this to go wrong, it
almost certainly won't work.

30:22.910 --> 30:25.590
It's what you Americans
would call a long shot.

30:26.170 --> 30:26.510
Hail Mary.

30:28.010 --> 30:28.890
I get it.

30:29.310 --> 30:32.210
The alternative is
to just do nothing.

30:33.330 --> 30:35.690
And to starve and
to kill each other

30:35.690 --> 30:37.990
and watch everything on
this planet go extinct,

30:38.370 --> 30:38.970
including us.

30:41.170 --> 30:41.850
So...

31:01.470 --> 31:03.590
That's a long time
to be in space.

31:04.470 --> 31:06.210
We'll be in comas
for most of it.

31:06.550 --> 31:07.910
But is that even safe?

31:08.270 --> 31:09.590
Nothing about this is safe.

31:25.090 --> 31:26.070
We only need three.

31:27.090 --> 31:31.570
A pilot, an engineer,
and a scientist.

31:36.190 --> 31:38.570
Commander Yao.

31:41.570 --> 31:43.970
I must have known you,
but I just don't remember.

31:45.070 --> 31:50.230
You make a funny face in
literally every picture.

31:51.750 --> 31:58.870
You must have been very
smart and strong and brave.

32:06.030 --> 32:08.310
First, I owe you
three bags of vodka.

32:09.870 --> 32:11.930
You seem to have
had a lot of friends.

32:13.110 --> 32:14.110
This picture of you,

32:14.530 --> 32:16.130
what looks like
sneaking into the Kremlin,

32:18.730 --> 32:19.290
is

32:19.890 --> 32:20.450
legendary.

32:22.690 --> 32:24.110
I wish you were still here.

32:26.190 --> 32:27.630
I wish I wasn't alone.

32:28.630 --> 32:32.370
I wish I was doing a better job.

32:32.370 --> 32:35.850
I just, uh...

32:38.110 --> 32:39.950
You were both very loved.

32:41.870 --> 32:43.830
You deserve much more than this.

32:46.230 --> 32:50.870
I'll do my best to make
sure that you don't...

32:51.550 --> 32:54.370
You know, that you didn't...

33:05.810 --> 33:07.170
I'll do my best.

33:17.338 --> 33:19.138
<i>Caution:
Override Outer Airlock Hatch</i>

34:11.390 --> 34:17.250
Approaching Tau Ceti orbit.
Prepare for engine cutoff.

34:18.410 --> 34:23.790
Fourteen. Thirteen.
Twelve. Eleven.

34:25.190 --> 34:25.930
Pilot detected.

34:26.510 --> 34:28.450
I'm not a pilot!

34:28.970 --> 34:31.790
What happens at
zero? I mean, what?

34:39.750 --> 34:42.450
You are now orbiting
Tau Ceti. Ah!

34:44.710 --> 34:48.430
What the fudging fudger!

34:49.170 --> 34:51.370
Ah! Ah! Ah!

34:51.370 --> 34:55.690
Petrovascope operational.
Petrovascope operational.

35:05.158 --> 35:06.696
<i>Location: Cockpit</i>

35:16.690 --> 35:17.890
It's Tau Ceti.

35:28.890 --> 35:33.050
You have a Petrova line,
but you're not dimming.

35:33.810 --> 35:34.230
Why?

35:45.190 --> 35:46.210
What is that?

36:02.630 --> 36:05.910
Blip-A detected.

36:06.930 --> 36:08.270
What's a Blip-A?

36:09.270 --> 36:10.870
Blip-A detected.

37:16.430 --> 37:17.950
No, no, no, no, no.

37:17.950 --> 37:19.170
Let's go, let's go, Mary.

37:19.170 --> 37:21.430
Mary. No, no, no,
no, no, no, no.

37:22.070 --> 37:22.670
Pilot detected!

37:22.870 --> 37:24.130
Please engage restraint.

37:24.590 --> 37:26.770
Pilot detected!

37:26.930 --> 37:27.610
Getting out of here.

37:27.790 --> 37:28.890
Engage spin drive.

37:29.270 --> 37:29.830
Engage spin drive.

37:29.850 --> 37:30.370
Incorrect.

37:30.790 --> 37:31.470
Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa.

37:31.530 --> 37:33.030
Welcome to the Hail Mary.

37:33.130 --> 37:33.870
Is it this thing?

37:39.210 --> 37:40.970
Erratic maneuver detected.

37:44.350 --> 37:44.750
Yuck.

37:48.450 --> 37:49.150
Oh, no.

38:00.750 --> 38:03.230
Blip-A detected.

38:06.150 --> 38:06.930
What does it want?

38:37.970 --> 38:38.650
What?

38:52.250 --> 38:53.910
Blip-B detected.

38:54.290 --> 38:54.930
What's up with this thing?

38:54.990 --> 38:58.070
Current distance from
Hail Mary is 800 meters.

38:58.070 --> 38:59.310
It's sending me something.

39:02.290 --> 39:03.790
It could be a message.

39:06.230 --> 39:06.910
Oh, no.

39:06.910 --> 39:07.830
It could be a bomb.

39:09.610 --> 39:10.270
Is it a bomb?

39:12.490 --> 39:12.890
Shields up!

39:12.910 --> 39:14.670
There are no shields
on board the Hail Mary.

39:14.690 --> 39:15.310
Why not?

39:16.450 --> 39:17.410
30 meters.

39:18.850 --> 39:19.810
20 meters.

39:20.170 --> 39:20.710
Ten.

39:31.090 --> 39:33.830
Well, I guess there's egg
on both our faces, huh Mary?

39:36.170 --> 39:37.030
What's that?

39:41.050 --> 39:43.570
Why is it moving so much
slower than the last one?

39:47.870 --> 39:49.130
They think I'm dumb.

39:53.910 --> 39:56.050
If we were going to
catch it, what would we do?

39:56.990 --> 39:59.270
Would you like to go on
a spacewalk, Dr. Grace?

40:05.450 --> 40:10.190
To begin your spacewalk, put on your
??? suit and proceed to the airlock.

40:21.350 --> 40:22.750
Yes!

40:33.813 --> 40:34.975
<i>Depressurization in progress</i>

40:58.670 --> 40:59.670
No.

41:01.250 --> 41:02.910
It's just crazy.

41:23.670 --> 41:26.470
Oh, God.

41:29.240 --> 41:30.295
<i>Location: Exterior Hail Mary
(outside of the ship)</i>

41:58.970 --> 42:01.770
Oh, God.

42:17.350 --> 42:20.150
Oh, God.

42:27.210 --> 42:29.610
Righty, tighty, lefty-loosey.

42:33.388 --> 42:34.287
<i>Xenon Indentification</i>

42:35.150 --> 42:36.210
Xenon's a gas.

42:36.310 --> 42:37.890
I think this thing's broken.

42:44.670 --> 42:49.910
We need equipment to analyze
the astrophage at Tau Ceti.

42:50.350 --> 42:50.650
Right,

42:51.870 --> 42:53.970
Most of this equipment
won't work in zero gravity.

42:54.230 --> 42:57.850
And we have a team to develop and build
zero gravity versions of this equipment.

42:57.990 --> 43:00.290
We would need years for
that, and we have months.

43:00.450 --> 43:01.330
What's the alternative?

43:01.810 --> 43:02.870
We make gravity.

43:03.770 --> 43:04.170
Centrifuge?

43:05.190 --> 43:05.710
Centrifuge.

43:05.710 --> 43:09.870
They use them to make butter
during the Civil War, actually.

43:10.730 --> 43:12.090
It's a fun fact.

44:07.610 --> 44:08.810
Lab operational.

44:20.950 --> 44:21.850
Still Xenon.

44:22.870 --> 44:25.790
Up is down, left is
right, Xenon's a solid.

44:26.390 --> 44:26.950
aliens are real,

44:27.250 --> 44:29.250
I'm wrong about everything
and everything's wrong.

44:34.330 --> 44:36.430
Lefty, tighty, righty-loosey.

44:38.030 --> 44:40.870
I mean... Oh no!

44:41.050 --> 44:42.610
Foreign presence detected.

44:42.686 --> 44:44.092
Foreign presence detected.

45:40.844 --> 45:42.577
<i>40 Eridani Sirius</i>

45:46.910 --> 45:48.290
You're a long way from home.

46:05.550 --> 46:07.170
I'm a long way from home, too.

46:26.150 --> 46:28.810
Blip-D detected.

50:39.850 --> 50:41.990
Is that me?

51:05.930 --> 51:07.010
I don't understand.

51:10.170 --> 51:21.570
You want me to go
back in my ship?

51:21.570 --> 51:30.150
But I just got here. Okay.

51:30.170 --> 51:38.410
Okay, I'll talk
to you later. Bye.

52:09.187 --> 52:11.007
<i>Location: Exterior Hail Mary
(outside of the ship)</i>

52:16.070 --> 52:18.330
What are they doing, Mary?

52:48.130 --> 52:50.150
It is not advised.

52:52.110 --> 52:52.630
Thank you, Mary.

52:55.394 --> 52:57.093
<i>Centrifugal Gravity System: Standing By</i>

52:57.093 --> 52:58.831
<i>Centrifugal Gravity System: Engaging</i>

53:43.831 --> 53:45.776
<i>Depressurization in progress</i>

54:03.690 --> 54:04.979
<i>Ext Pressure: 21.1 kPa
Ext Temp: 22° C</i>

54:04.210 --> 54:05.610
What?

54:26.110 --> 54:30.030
Oh my. This is new.

54:42.550 --> 54:43.850
Anybody home?

54:47.290 --> 54:49.550
I like what you've
done with the gravity.

54:56.450 --> 55:03.830
I made you a ship. It's ramen.

55:07.010 --> 55:07.850
I only made one.

55:07.850 --> 55:12.670
I'm not sure how
many of you there are.

56:31.350 --> 56:33.570
Hi. No, no, no. I'm
sorry. I'm sorry.

56:34.670 --> 56:36.670
You scared me when you went...

57:32.610 --> 57:34.010
Oh

57:58.570 --> 58:05.930
Can't seem to see your face...
Mysterious! Faces are overrated.

58:07.890 --> 58:08.150
Oh

58:18.870 --> 58:20.870
You like tapping, huh?

58:51.870 --> 58:56.390
You're pointing! You're
not tapping. Sorry.

59:22.670 --> 59:25.530
I don't have one
of these. I love it!

59:26.690 --> 59:28.210
Thank you.

59:31.330 --> 59:34.610
put this on my head?

59:36.570 --> 59:38.810
Take off my head?

59:40.170 --> 59:42.170
Take my helmet off?

59:43.010 --> 59:44.150
No,

59:49.650 --> 59:51.650
That's a big ask. Oh.

59:56.850 --> 01:00:01.910
This is taking a turn. Thank you for
the... What I hope is not handcuffs.

01:00:03.150 --> 01:00:05.370
I'm sorry about the
whole helmet thing.

01:00:06.230 --> 01:00:16.190
Unfortunately, I need
oxygen to breathe, so...

01:00:16.590 --> 01:00:17.770
Two rings of eight.

01:00:21.970 --> 01:00:22.670
O2,

01:00:26.410 --> 01:00:27.210
you little rascal.

01:00:30.070 --> 01:00:31.550
This is oxygen.

01:00:35.750 --> 01:00:38.970
I still don't think I
can do it, though. Sorry.

01:00:40.210 --> 01:00:44.030
It's just, uh... If I'm
wrong, I'm really wrong.

01:02:06.530 --> 01:02:10.030
It's the Petrova line.

01:02:12.990 --> 01:02:14.330
We're here for the same reason.

01:02:15.070 --> 01:02:16.750
You have a Petrova
line problem, too.

01:02:17.010 --> 01:02:17.930
You need to solve it.

01:02:18.130 --> 01:02:19.090
I need to solve it.

01:02:19.270 --> 01:02:20.310
That's why you made me this.

01:02:24.090 --> 01:02:25.530
I'm going to take that as a yes.

01:02:26.410 --> 01:02:29.050
If we're going to save our planets,
we have to learn how to communicate.

01:02:29.730 --> 01:02:32.450
You know, they say math
is the universal language.

01:02:32.590 --> 01:02:35.870
I thought maybe we could learn how to
communicate. Wait, find out if that's true.

01:02:36.330 --> 01:02:37.270
You see the numbers?

01:02:39.910 --> 01:02:42.250
Oh, you want this?

01:02:43.410 --> 01:02:43.810
Whoa!

01:02:44.350 --> 01:02:45.450
Christmas Eve, that is...

01:02:46.170 --> 01:02:47.090
It's really hot in there.

01:02:47.330 --> 01:02:48.050
Is that ammonia?

01:02:50.670 --> 01:02:52.190
Anyway, that's...
Look, see the numbers?

01:02:52.890 --> 01:02:54.090
they're on the other side.

01:02:54.410 --> 01:02:55.230
Do it again.

01:02:55.870 --> 01:02:57.870
If you do it again,
don't let it snap back.

01:02:58.450 --> 01:02:59.570
don't do it.

01:02:59.630 --> 01:03:00.710
Hold it like that,

01:03:01.070 --> 01:03:01.710
and you look.

01:03:05.350 --> 01:03:05.750
Wow.

01:03:06.610 --> 01:03:07.010
Wow.

01:03:07.990 --> 01:03:09.750
How about something else?

01:03:10.210 --> 01:03:11.510
Look at this.

01:03:12.630 --> 01:03:13.210
Clock.

01:03:14.710 --> 01:03:16.310
We both have time, right?

01:03:16.650 --> 01:03:17.530
These are the hands,

01:03:18.270 --> 01:03:19.350
and these are the numbers.

01:03:19.630 --> 01:03:20.150
One, two, three.

01:03:20.170 --> 01:03:25.770
They point to the numbers. And if you'll notice,
there's numbers there and there's also numbers here.

01:03:29.170 --> 01:03:29.710
Okay.

01:03:33.390 --> 01:03:34.410
It is dark.

01:03:40.640 --> 01:03:58.640
I got an idea. Wait. Don't... Yeah. Don't go
anywhere. Stay. Oh, yeah. Um... I'm Grace.

01:04:01.100 --> 01:04:10.720
I'm gonna call you Rocky. You know, because
you look like a giant rock. Oh. I'm fine.

01:04:22.540 --> 01:04:26.480
Echolocation. Right? You
need surfaces to see. Try this.

01:04:30.120 --> 01:04:31.440
You see the numbers?

01:04:34.240 --> 01:04:39.600
What is that? Is that
good? Jazz hands means good.

01:04:41.840 --> 01:04:54.400
do this. Your version of this is our thumbs up.
No, that's thumbs down. We do the thumbs up.

01:04:55.840 --> 01:04:57.040
It's close enough.

01:04:59.040 --> 01:05:03.040
You want me to wait?
I wait? Yeah. No.

01:05:05.340 --> 01:05:08.920
I'm really, uh, really excited
to be working with you on this.

01:05:08.920 --> 01:05:15.120
Fired up. I'm sorry I'm talking so much. It's just
that I haven't been around anyone in a long time.

01:05:19.480 --> 01:05:21.200
What have we got here?

01:05:32.720 --> 01:05:37.040
It's a clock. I
showed you a clock

01:05:40.380 --> 01:05:44.960
You're showing me a clock.
We're, uh, clock bros.

01:05:51.450 --> 01:05:58.430
Right. Um, I gotta be honest.
I'm not sure I'm getting all of

01:06:07.660 --> 01:06:09.040
